"response_text": "Analysis of the mean initial risk attitudes across simulations reveals a distribution centered below the baseline risk-att-init value of 0.5, with values clustering between 0.01 and 0.18. This range reflects heterogeneous risk preferences among households despite uniform E-RO behavioral strategies under homogeneous conditions. Early measurements (e.g., columns 1–3) show higher initial risk attitudes (~0.07–0.08) compared to later values in some sequences, though no clear temporal progression is evident due to repeated fluctuations. Negative values (e.g., -0.11, -0.04) indicate occasional divergence toward risk-seeking behavior, likely responding to contextual factors like grass resource availability or climatic variability.   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   Situated within the E-RO baseline, these variations suggest that while uniformly rational agents (E-RO) prioritize long-term resource conservation without strategic switching (SL2-strategy-switch? disabled), their risk attitudes mediate responses to environmental shocks. For example, agents with higher risk tolerance (e.g., 0.18) may adopt more aggressive stocking strategies during favorable conditions, risking overgrazing but securing short-term gains. Conversely, slightly risk-averse variants (e.g., 0.01) might understock, reducing pressure on pasture biomass but potentially sacrificing livelihood returns.   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   \\\\n   Observed correlations between risk attitudes and outcomes—such as pasture biomass stability and household resilience—imply that even within a single strategy class (E-RO), heterogeneity in risk sensitivity could amplify or dampen system-wide shocks. Decision makers are advised to consider how tailored risk-management frameworks (e.g., flexible stocking quotas, social safety nets) might mitigate disparities in household outcomes driven by innate risk preferences. Furthermore, the lack of social learning (E-RO-SL1 inactive) under homogeneous conditions underscores the need for institutional interventions to foster knowledge-sharing practices, which could align risk-prone behaviors with collective resource sustainability goals.   \\\\n"
}

